    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "- `nvim --version`: 0.2 (In future)\r\n- Vim (version: ) behaves differently? no\r\n- Operating system/version: Windows 7, 8, 10, etc.\r\n- Terminal name/version:\r\n- `$TERM`:\r\n\r\n### Actual behaviour\r\nI don't know.\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\nRecognize Capslock as a hotkey;\r\n recognize a single Shift stroke as a hotkey;\r\nrecognize Alt-Enter stroke as a hotkey\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce using `nvim -u NORC`\r\nI don't know.\r\n```\r\nnvim -u NORC\r\n\r\n```\r\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "\"alt\" (AKA \"meta\") combinations, including `<a-enter>` are already recognized, even in terminal nvim. Try it:\r\n\r\n    nnoremap <a-enter> :echo \"hi, you just pressed alt+enter\"<cr>\r\n\r\nSingle-shift doesn't currently have a representation in vim/nvim's key model:  `<Shift>` is not recognized:\r\n\r\n```\r\n:nn <shift> :echom localtime().\"shift\"<cr>\r\n:call nvim_input('<shift>')  \" no message written, `<shift>` map wasn't resolved\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut Neovim GUIs can certainly capture \"shift\", and then send it via `nvim_input()` as shown above. We just need to add `<shift>` as a recognized key to map to.\r\n\r\nI suppose we could add `<capslock>` as well. Again, bear in mind that it's up to the GUI to capture \"capslock\" and send it to `nvim`. \r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/2345 discusses a different limitation: ctrl+shift. (Note: again, as mentioned above, \"alt\" does _not_ have that limitation. \"Alt\" maps are fully supported.)\r\n\r\n",
